content.description: Without knowing more of the history of this area I can't claim FA but seems like something that may get ignored. Also a nice route to do to get some height. Starts as a crack/chimney climb. Once you hit the tree in the crack go left straight up to top out. You know you're about to top out when you see beer cans in a crack. You can walk off or setup a top belay.
content.protection: Cams .4-5 multiple 3s. Walk off top or build anchor
content.location: South end of castle Rock. To the right of a bolted overhang route.

content.description: A meandering route that changes character often along the way. Follow the flake up and then exit left to a stance below the roof. Climb the small dihedral and move back right towards the tree on some sandy jugs. On the mini headwall above awaits an interesting crux and the chains. Please don't climb if the rock is wet!
content.location: First route on the west wall if approaching from the road. Climbs the flake on the right side of Dihedral Dance wall

content.description: Nice face route, fairly sustained. The crux is right at the top. You can clip the anchors of the crux holds if your tall, or its a couple more tough moves to gain the ledge.
content.protection: 6 bolts, webbing and rap ring anchor.
content.location: To find this you have to do a short scramble up and left from the base of the mixed route to just beneath a pine tree.

climbs.name: Mark it Zero!
climbs.fa: Unknown .  I climbed it first in 2009 - Please let me know!

content.description: Begin at flaring crack (usually filled with beetles) and climb up and left, 30 feet, to crack system just below the first overhang.  Pull the overhang and advance to second overhang (crux).  Continue up face using bomber holds to a jam crack.  This crack leads you to a point where the angle eases and eventually tops out on a nice, roomy belay ledge.  Finish climb or continue to scramble up to Castle Rock summit.  A fun and varied climb!
content.protection: Top-rope.  Not sure if the sandstone would hold trad gear...don't want to find out!
content.location: Right around the corner from "Best Jams" (climber's right)

content.description: Start with left hand gaston notch and right hand undercling jug. Climb directly up the airy arete.
content.location: South side of cliffband next to some bolted slab routes.

content.description: A fun climb with two distinct cruxes in totally different styles. The starting slab leads to a juggy roof reminiscent of Riverboat Gambler at Necedah, albeit harder and more engaging.Start on thin and cruxy holds to a good groove and the first bolt. Enjoy the feaured slab, eventually moving left a bit before mantling to the break. Climb the ramp to the sandy roof, find the jugs and pull hard! Once you surmount the roof, romp up to the chains.Please don't climb if the rock is wet.
content.location: Right in the middle of the Dihedral Dance wall on the southwest side of the cliff. Climbs the center slab

content.description: Move up the slab and over roof using 4 bolts, finish  using small gear in the crack. The crux is at the last bolt getting into the crack.

Head up the slab through some loose rock, some neat moves lead you into the small overhang on positive holds. After pulling over the small roof head out and left though the crux to gain a rest ledge...After clipping the next couple bolts you can either move out to the exposed arete (5.10/11), or head up direct(desperate feeling 5.12ish).

Amazing route like none other in Wisconsin. Moves straight up the arete, utilizes a bunch of heals to stop the barndoor, and lots of pinches and slaps up the arete. The crux comes up high with some thin vertical seams.
content.protection: 6 bolts, webbing and rap ring anchors.
content.location: Located up and left of the mixed climb starts right on the obvious arete.

content.description: Located on the sunny side of the bluff, this area features long and/or exposed airy aretes, and faces. It looks like there is the possibility for a few long trad lines as well.
